Tracking republican party changes

Calculate net change in Republican-controlled seats per state between 2021-2024

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
##

##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

changes_rep <- read_csv("All_Years_Combined.csv")
## New names:
## • `` -> `...1`
## Rows: 200 Columns: 15
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (7): STATE, Senate
## other, Total
## House, House
## other, Leg.Control, Gov.Par...
## dbl (8): ...1, Total.Seats, Total.Senate
## , Senate.Dem, Senate.Rep, House.Dem...
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
changes_filtered <- changes_rep %>% 
  filter(Year %in% c(2021, 2024))

changes_filtered <- changes_filtered %>% 
  mutate(Senate.Rep = as.numeric(Senate.Rep),
         House.Rep = as.numeric(House.Rep)
         )

changes_filtered <- changes_filtered %>% 
  mutate(Total_Rep = Senate.Rep + House.Rep)

# Reshaping so each state's Rep seat counts for 2021 and 2024 are in separate columns 

library(tidyr)



changes_wide <- changes_filtered %>% 
  select(STATE, Year, Total_Rep) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = Year, values_from = Total_Rep, names_prefix = "Year_")

# Calculate net changes - difference in Rep seats between 2024 and 2021 
changes_wide <- changes_wide %>% 
  mutate(Net_Change = Year_2024 - Year_2021)

print(changes_wide)
## # A tibble: 50 × 4

# Sort by net change 
changes_wide_sorted <- changes_wide %>% 
  arrange(desc(Net_Change))
print(changes_wide_sorted)

Carolina, Arizona, New Mexico, Utah, California, Minnesota, Oregon, S. Dakota, Tennessee had net positive changes (became more republican controlled in 3 years)

Visualizing net change in Republican seats

library(ggplot2)
changes_wide_sorted %>% 
         filter(STATE != "Nebraska") %>% 
         ggplot(aes(x = reorder(STATE, Net_Change), y = Net_Change, fill = Net_Change > 0)) + 
  geom_col() + 
  coord_flip() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "red", "FALSE" = "green"),
                    labels = c("Decrease", "Increase")) + 
  labs(
    title = "Net Change in Republican-Controlled Seats by State (2021-2024)",
    x = "State",
    y = "Net change in Republican Seats",
    fill = "Change Type"
  ) + 
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) + 
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10),
    legend.position = "bottom"
  )

Changes in State Control from 2021 to 2024

state_c <- read_csv("All_Years_Combined.csv")
## New names:
## Rows: 200 Columns: 15
## ── Column specification
## ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── Delimiter: "," chr
## (7): STATE, Senate other, Total House, House other, Leg.Control, Gov.Par... dbl
## (8): ...1, Total.Seats, Total.Senate , Senate.Dem, Senate.Rep, House.Dem...
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data. ℹ
## Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
## • `` -> `...1`
state_c_filtered <- state_c %>% 
  filter(Year %in% c(2021, 2024)) %>% 
  select(STATE, Year, State.Control)

state_control_wide <- state_c_filtered %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Year, values_from = State.Control, names_prefix = "Year_")

# remove Nebraska 
state_control_wide <- state_control_wide %>% 
  filter(STATE != "Nebraska")

# New column for change
  state_control_wide <- state_control_wide %>%
    mutate(Change = ifelse(Year_2021 == Year_2024, "No Change", 
                         paste(Year_2021, "->", Year_2024)))
  
change_counts <- state_control_wide %>% 
  count(Change)

ggplot(change_counts, aes(x = reorder(Change, n), y = n, fill = Change)) + 
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) + 
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Changes in State Government Control (2021 to 2024)",
    x = "Control Transition",
    y = "Number of States"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14)

Most states did not experience a change in government control when comparing 2024 to 2021

Show which states made which transitions

state_c_filtered <- state_c %>% 
  filter(Year %in% c(2021, 2024)) %>% 
  select(STATE, Year, State.Control)


state_control_wide <- state_c_filtered %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Year, values_from = State.Control, names_prefix = "Year_")

# Remove Nebraska (nonpartisan)
state_control_wide <- state_control_wide %>% 
  filter(STATE != "Nebraska")

# Create 'Change' label
state_control_wide <- state_control_wide %>%
  mutate(Change = ifelse(Year_2021 == Year_2024, "No Change", 
                         paste(Year_2021, "→", Year_2024)))

# Plot: Which states changed and how
ggplot(state_control_wide %>% filter(Change != "No Change"),
       aes(x = reorder(STATE, Change), y = Change, fill = Change)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(
    "Divided→Rep" = "red",
    "Divided → Rep" = "red",
    "Divided→Dem" = "blue",
    "Divided → Dem" = "blue",
    "Dem→Divided" = "purple",
    "Dem → Divided" = "purple",
    "Rep→Divided" = "pink",
    "Rep → Divided" = "pink"
  )) +
  labs(
    title = "States That Changed Government Control (2021 to 2024)",
    x = "State",
    y = "Control Change"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14)

Find which year had most Republican state governments

state_data <- read_csv("All_Years_Combined.csv")
## New names:
## Rows: 200 Columns: 15
## ── Column specification
## ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── Delimiter: "," chr
## (7): STATE, Senate other, Total House, House other, Leg.Control, Gov.Par... dbl
## (8): ...1, Total.Seats, Total.Senate , Senate.Dem, Senate.Rep, House.Dem...
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data. ℹ
## Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
## • `` -> `...1`
rep_control_by_year <- state_data %>% 
  filter(State.Control == "Rep") %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarise(Num_Rep_States = n()) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Num_Rep_States))

print(rep_control_by_year)
## # A tibble: 4 × 2
##    Year Num_Rep_States
##   <dbl>          <int>
## 1  2021             23
## 2  2022             23
## 3  2024             23
## 4  2023             22

2021, 2022, 2024 - 23 states had Republican governments. 2023 drop to 22. Not really significant finding here in increased conservatism.

# Remove Nebraska (nonpartisan)
state_data <- state_data %>%
  filter(STATE != "Nebraska")

# Count number of states under each control type by year
state_control_trend_yearly <- state_data %>%
  group_by(Year, State.Control) %>%
  summarise(Num_States = n(), .groups = "drop")

# View summary (optional)
print(state_control_trend_yearly)
## # A tibble: 12 × 3
##     Year State.Control Num_States
##    <dbl> <chr>              <int>
##  1  2021 Dem                   15
##  2  2021 Divided               11
##  3  2021 Rep                   23
##  4  2022 Dem                   14
##  5  2022 Divided               12
##  6  2022 Rep                   23
##  7  2023 Dem                   17
##  8  2023 Divided               10
##  9  2023 Rep                   22
## 10  2024 Dem                   15
## 11  2024 Divided               11
## 12  2024 Rep                   23
# Plot the trend over time
ggplot(state_control_trend_yearly, aes(x = Year, y = Num_States, fill = State.Control)) +
  geom_col(position = "stack") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Rep" = "red", "Dem" = "blue", "Divided" = "purple")) +
  labs(
    title = "Trend in State Government Control by Year",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Number of States",
    fill = "State Control"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14)

Not really much change in state government control by year. More states were democrat controlled in 2023

State Control - When the same party holds both legislative chambers and the governorship, that party has state control. When any of those three points of power is held by another party, state control is divided.
